Hi @hunkebun, thank you for your interest in the greenery around you. As we transit to a City in Nature, we have implemented measures to attract and support native biodiversity. This includes habitat enhancement and restoration projects in our parks, and multi-tiered planting that resemble the natural structure of our forests along Nature Ways. Nature Ways are curated to provide ground cover that attracts butterflies, bees and other pollinators such as sunbirds. We have also allowed spontaneous greenery to grow on several slopes along our roads, which not only provides food and shelter for animals, but also provides natural protection and support for the slope. We will continue to introduce more naturalistic landscapes that will attract more biodiversity, such as the grasslands at the Jurong Lake Gardens, as well as in our parks like Tampines Eco-Green, Coney Island and Thomson and Windsor Nature Parks. Going forward, for feedback or enquiries, you can reach us via our website at: https://www.nparks.gov.sg/feedback. Hope this clarifies! 😊
